<TITLE> Stocks end upbeat on banks, blue chips </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 7 (bdnews24.com)--Dhaka stocks ended upbeat on the opening day of the week, with the general index gaining by 1 percent, driven mainly by banks and blue chip shares. The benchmark general index or the DGEN rose by 56.06 points to close at 5490.10. The all share price index or the DSI ended at 4512.64, up by 38.77 points or 0.86 percent, while the DSE-20 blue chip index shot up 2.23 percent or 68.43 points. But investor participation was rather low reflected on the day's turnover of Tk 9.86 billion. The previous week's (Jan 31 - Feb 4) saw a daily average turnover of Tk 15.54 billion. Brokerage house officials said that the SEC decision of a cut in margin loan ratio resulted in relatively low turnover. On Feb 3, the market regulator adjusted the margin loan ratio to 1:1, effective from Sunday. "The reduced loan facility is the reason behind the low trading today (Sunday)" an official of Latif Securities told bdnews24.com Gainers outnumbered losers 135 to 96 while nine issues remained unchanged. Banks were the day's driving factor as the whole sector moved up with most of the non-bank financial institutions following. Mutual funds and insurers ended mixed, power entities remained more or less steady with slight deviations, but the day turned out be a bad one for oil shares. The only gas distribution company listed with the bourse, Titas Gas also edged down. The pharmaceuticals and chemical sector, which houses some of the market heavyweights closed mixed, also with slight deviations while IT shares fell. Meanwhile, the market bigwig Grameenphone, traded between Tk 296.90 and 290, edged up 0.58 percent to close at Tk 292.60. It topped the board as turnover leader with shares worth Tk 463.647 million changing hands. Second-in-line, South East Bank had a turnover of Tk 386.944 million followed by Beximco which saw shares traded Tk 386.944 million. Mercantile Bank and Premier Bank followed with turnovers of Tk 362.063 million and Tk 309.418 million respectively. DBH First Mutual Fund, Lanka Bangla Finance, Lafarge Surma Cement, AB Bank and Premier Bank were the other turnover leaders.
